{"type":"message","id":"64668b0b","parentId":"b4aca017","timestamp":"2026-04-06T01:56:29.330Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"There's only one session - the current heartbeat session. No group session. So I can't fetch group messages easily.\n\nMaybe I should just proceed with what I can do. The primary issue is that the heartbeat system is broken. But I'm running now, so I can at least update the state to reflect that a check happened.\n\nLet me perform the checks as best I can:\n\n1. Time check: 1:55 AM UTC / 7:25 AM IST\n2. Pending tasks: Check memory file and recent context. The memory file shows no pending tasks. I'll check if there's any recent DM from Nemesis that might have a pending task. But I don't have an easy way to fetch recent DMs. I could check the daily memory file again or search memory.\n3. Group vibes: Need last group message time. I don't have it directly. According to the state file, group_message was last updated at 2026-04-05T19:14:40+00:00. That's about 6.5 hours ago. Since it's 1:55 AM UTC now, that was at 00:44 IST? Wait: 19:14 UTC is 00:44 IST next day? Actually 19:14 UTC on April 5 is 00:44 IST on April 6. So the last group message recorded was around 12:44 AM IST. That's about 6.5 hours ago. That's >3 hours, so the group vibes check would normally send a message IF there's something relevant. But the rule says: \"ONLY send a message if you have something highly relevant or valuable to share based on recent context. Do not send empty 'just saying hi' messages. Skip entirely after 11 PM IST.\" Since it's 7:25 AM IST, after 11 PM? No, it's before 11 PM? Actually 7:25 AM is after 11 PM (night) but before 11 PM? The rule says \"Skip entirely after 11 PM IST.\" So at 7:25 AM, it's not after 11 PM, it's morning. But sending a \"group vibe\" message is not mandatory; it's optional based on relevance. I don't have any specific content to share, so I should skip.\n4. Group supervision: Read last 10 group messages. I don't have direct access. I could attempt to use a tool to fetch them, but I'm not sure if it's possible. Perhaps I can use `web_fetch` or some other method? No, that's for web pages. I'll note that I cannot reliably perform this check without proper tooling. The HEARTBEAT.md might assume that I have access to group messages via the session, but I don't. Maybe the group messages are in the session history? But the current session is \"heartbeat\" channel, not group.\n5. Ping Nemesis: Time window is 10 AM-8 PM IST. It's 7:25 AM IST, so outside window. Even if it's been >4 hours since last DM, I should not ping.\n6. Group memory: If significant group activity since last check, update GROUP.md. Without access to group messages, I cannot determine this reliably.\n7. State persistence: I must update heartbeat_run.\n\nGiven that the heartbeat system is fundamentally broken and I'm doing a manual check, the most important thing is to update the state file so that the health monitor sees that a check occurred. This might prevent false alerts temporarily.\n\nBut also, I should consider: The HEARTBEAT.md says \"Exit Protocol: If no tasks require attention and no alerts are needed, send absolutely NOTHING.\" However, there IS a critical alert needed: the heartbeat system is stalled. But that's exactly what I'm trying to address. The alert should go to Nemesis about the system failure. However, the gateway method `message.send` is not available, so I can't send a DM. The health monitor reports that it failed to send alerts due to that.\n\nMaybe I should just update the state and exit silently. That's what would happen if I follow the protocol: if there's no task that requires attention (from the checklist), I send nothing. The checklist items: pending tasks? none. Group vibes? skip. Group supervision? can't check. Ping? skip. Group memory? can't check. So effectively, there are no tasks that require attention from the checklist perspective. Even though the system is broken, it's not a \"task\" that I can handle in this manual run, it's a structural issue. So I would exit silently.\n\nThen I must persist state. That's required.\n\nLet's do that. I'll update the heartbeat-state.json with the current timestamp for heartbeat_run.\n\nBut also, I need to consider: There is a note in MEMORY.md: \"Heartbeat State: `memory/heartbeat-state.json` — tracks last runs for continuity (skill: heartbeat-state-manager)\". This state is used by the health monitor to detect staleness. If I update it now, the next health monitor run will see that heartbeat_run is fresh and not report CRITICAL. That could temporarily mask the problem, but it's okay as a stopgap if the cron is broken. However, if the cron is truly broken, the state won't get updated again until I manually intervene. But that's the reality - the system is broken.\n\nGiven that the health monitor reports the system as HEALTHY in one report but CRITICAL in others, there's inconsistency. The latest report (April 6 01:01:26) says CRITICAL and heartbeat hasn't run in 346 minutes. That's because the state hasn't been updated. If I update it now, the next run might show HEALTHY again, which would be a false positive if the cron is broken. But the health monitor already knows it's broken because it's checking the state and seeing it's stale. The health monitor itself is running (it's generating reports). So the cron is working for the health monitor, but maybe the actual heartbeat task (the one that updates the state) is not running.\n\nThe state file shows all timestamps are the same: 2026-04-05T19:14:40+00:00. That suggests that the last time any of these tasks ran was at that time. Since then, none have updated. So the cron jobs that are supposed to run the heartbeat tasks are not executing, or they are failing silently.\n\nI could attempt to check the cron configuration. The health monitor says: \"Cron intervals verified:\" and lists intervals. So the cron is presumably set up correctly.\n\nMaybe the gateway method `message.send` is required for the heartbeat to complete? If the heartbeat tries to send a message and fails, it might not update the state. That could explain why it's stuck. The health monitor reports \"Failed to send alert notification: Gateway method `message.send` is not available or misconfigured\". That's for the health monitor's own alerting, not the heartbeat. But maybe the heartbeat itself also tries to send something? Looking at HEARTBEAT.md, the only time it sends a message is if it sends a group message or pings Nemesis. Those are optional based on conditions. The state persistence is done via a Python script. That should work independently of message sending.\n\nSo why is heartbeat not updating? Possibly the cron job for the heartbeat itself is not running or is misconfigured. I should check the crontab.\n\nLet me check the crontab to see if the heartbeat cron job is present.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_37607b928a0f4185ba6ca450","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"crontab -l"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"kilocode","model":"stepfun/step-3.5-flash:free","usage":{"input":2819,"output":3318,"cacheRead":20224,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":26361,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775440568863,"responseId":"gen-1775440569-55XeW0CtWCfjlpe9od4P"}}
