{"type":"message","id":"ee8b4b21","parentId":"407d2073","timestamp":"2026-04-06T08:26:53.543Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting. The state shows:\n- heartbeat_run: 07:56:44 UTC (that's recent, maybe the heartbeat cron job ran and updated it? Actually earlier I ran update_state manually at 06:59:08. But this shows 07:56:44. Possibly the heartbeat cron job itself ran later and updated it, or my last update set a different timestamp? Actually my last update used the script which sets the timestamp to current time. According to the command I ran: `python3 ~/.openclaw/workspace/skills/heartbeat-state-manager/scripts/update_state.py --field heartbeat_run --field nemesis_ping`. That should set heartbeat_run to the current time (the time of execution). I executed that at around 06:59:08. But the file now shows 07:56:44. That's about 57 minutes later. Perhaps the script uses a different timestamp source? Or maybe I mis-ordered: I sent DM at 06:59, then ran update_state. But the file shows 07:56:44. That seems like maybe I ran it again later? Let's examine the transcript. In the previous session, after sending the DM, I executed update_state. That was in the same turn. The transcript shows:\n\nTool calls:\n  - message.send (success)\n  - exec(update_state) (executed)\n\nSo that should have updated immediately. The timestamp in the file after that should be ~06:59. But now it's 07:56:44. Possibly the system clock changed? Or maybe there was another heartbeat run in between that updated it to 07:56:44. The health monitor at 08:00 says group_message and git_push haven't run in 767 minutes. That's from the state file's group_message and git_push fields, which are still 19:14:40 on April 5. So those haven't been updated. The heartbeat_run field was updated by the last manual run. So the 07:56:44 is from my last update? But my update was at 06:59, not 07:56. Could be that the system time is off? Or maybe the script adds some delay? Let's not overthink; I'll trust the file as current.\n\nCurrent values:\n- heartbeat_run: 07:56:44 UTC (approx 28 min ago at 08:25) -> OK\n- group_message: 19:14:40 UTC April 5 (~13h ago) -> >3h, but no relevant content to share\n- git_push: 19:14:40 UTC April 5 (~13h ago) -> already alerted Nemesis\n- nemesis_ping: 06:59:08 UTC (~1h 26m ago) -> <4h\n- memory_review: still old but not critical yet\n\nNow, the health monitor at 08:00 flagged group_message and git_push as critical because thresholds: group_message critical ≥6h (360 min) actually the health monitor says threshold 360 min for group_message? In the summary: \"group_message task hasn't run in 767 minutes (threshold: 360 min)\". So 767 min > 360 -> critical. git_push threshold 360 min as well. So both are critical.\n\nBut note: the thresholds in the health monitor differ from those in HEARTBEAT.md? The health monitor uses its own thresholds. According to HEARTBEAT.md, the thresholds are:\n- heartbeat_run: warning ≥45 min, critical ≥60 min\n- group_message: warning ≥4h (240 min), critical ≥6h (360 min)\n- nemesis_ping: warning ≥6h, critical ≥8h\n- git_push: warning ≥3h (180 min), critical ≥6h (360 min)\n- memory_review: warning ≥26h, critical ≥30h\n\nSo indeed group_message and git_push are >6h, so critical. They haven't been updated because the underlying cron jobs haven't executed. The heartbeat_run itself is fine because I manually updated it.\n\nThus, the system state is that the cron scheduler is not running these jobs. That's the root cause. I've already notified Nemesis via DM about git_push being overdue. I could also mention that group_message is overdue, but that's just my own group engagement; it's not a system failure per se. Actually the group_message field tracks when I last sent a message to the group. That is an action that I perform, not a cron job. The health monitor's group_message threshold refers to when I last sent a group message. That is not a cron job; it's a metric. If I haven't sent a group message in >6h, it's a warning that I'm not engaging. But it's not a cron job failure. The git_push is a cron job. So the two are different: group_message staleness is my own inaction; git_push staleness is a cron job not running.\n\nThus, the critical issues are:\n- I haven't sent a group message in >6h (but I have a reason: no relevant content, and it's okay to skip if nothing to say? The HEARTBEAT.md says \"ONLY send a message if you have something highly relevant or valuable to share based on recent context.\" So it's okay to not send if no relevant context. But the health monitor still flags it as critical. Maybe that's intended to prompt me to check if there's something relevant. I've checked and found nothing. So I'll not send. That's fine. The health monitor's alert is just a signal; it doesn't force me to send if there's nothing relevant. So I can ignore that particular threshold violation if justified.\n- git_push hasn't run. That's a real cron job failure. I've already alerted Nemesis. So that's addressed.\n\nSo now I just need to persist state and exit.\n\nBut before I exit, the HEARTBEAT.md also says \"Group supervision: Read last 10 group messages.\" I haven't done that because I can't. However, maybe I can simulate that by reading the GROUP.md file, which contains some group context but not the last 10 messages. But that's not the same. The instruction might be to read from the actual chat. Since I don't have that capability, I might have to note that I cannot perform that check. But the protocol says if nothing needs attention, reply HEARTBEAT_OK. I think the expectation is that if I can't read the group messages due to tool limitations, I should still proceed. I've done what I can.\n\nGiven that I've already sent a DM alert about the git push, and there's no further action required (I already checked group vibes and decided not to send), I should now just persist state and reply HEARTBEAT_OK.\n\nBut wait: The health monitor summary says \"Alert Delivery: Failed to send notifications (gateway method error: `message.send` unknown)\". That's concerning because if the health monitor's automatic alerts are failing, I need to ensure Nemesis gets the alerts. I've manually sent one DM. But what about future health monitor runs? The health monitor might still fail to send alerts. That could be a problem. Should I also notify Nemesis about this gateway method error? Possibly, but that might be double-dipping. However, it's a separate issue: the automated alert system is broken. I could include that in a DM as well. But I already sent a DM; maybe I should send another with that info? The HEARTBEAT.md says to ping only if relevant alert. This is relevant. But I could also just wait until next heartbeat? But the health monitor may keep failing to send alerts. That's serious. I should mention it.\n\nLet me consider: The health monitor's output says \"gateway method `message.send` unknown\". That suggests the health monitor script is trying to call a method that doesn't exist. But I used `message` action = \"send\" successfully earlier. So maybe the health monitor uses a different RPC method or the gateway's method name is something else? Actually I used the tool `message` with action \"send\". That tool uses the gateway behind the scenes. It worked. So maybe the health monitor script incorrectly calls `message.send` as a direct RPC, but the correct method is something else. Or maybe the health monitor runs in a different context (like a subagent) where the message tool is not available. Anyway, it's broken. I should inform Nemesis so he can fix the health monitor's alert delivery.\n\nBut I'm currently in a heartbeat poll. According to HEARTBEAT.md, I should check pending tasks and alerts. This is definitely an alert-worthy issue: the health monitor cannot send alerts. That means if other issues occur, Nemesis won't be notified automatically. That's critical. I should include that in a DM. But I already sent a DM about git_push. Should I send a follow-up DM? Possibly, but the HEARTBEAT.md says \"Do not DM Nemesis just to report that a task was completed.\" That's not relevant. And \"ONLY ping Nemesis if there is a relevant alert, a pending task reminder, or something highly specific to his interests.\" This is a relevant alert about system reliability. So it's okay to send another DM, but maybe I should combine them? However, the DM I already sent might have been read already. I can send another with updated info.\n\nAlternatively, I could wait until the next heartbeat when I would naturally check and then send a combined update. But the health monitor itself is part of the system; if it's failing to send alerts, that's urgent. I've already manually sent one alert about git_push, but the health monitor will continue to run and fail. Nemesis should know that the automated alert path is broken.\n\nThus, I will send a DM now with the details: \"The health monitor's automated alert delivery is failing due to gateway method error. I've sent manual alerts, but you should fix the health monitor script or gateway config to ensure future alerts are delivered automatically.\"\n\nBut careful: The user is sending me heartbeat prompts regularly. They might be expecting me to just respond with HEARTBEAT_OK if no action. But I have a critical issue: the automated alert delivery is failing. That's something Nemesis needs to know. So I should act.\n\nLet me re-read the HEARTBEAT.md instructions. It doesn't explicitly say what to do if the health monitor itself is failing. But it's part of the system health. The \"Ping Nemesis\" check says: \"Check if it's been 4+ hours since last DM (between 10 AM–8 PM IST). ONLY ping Nemesis if there is a relevant alert, a pending task reminder, or something highly specific to his interests.\" The failing alert delivery is a relevant alert. So I should ping. I'm within 10 AM-8 PM IST (1:55 PM IST). So it's fine.\n\nI'll send a DM.\n\nBut I need to be mindful: The health monitor might also be checking for \"group_message\" staleness, and if I send a DM now, that will update nemesis_ping and heartbeat_run. That's fine.\n\nSo plan:\n1. Send DM to Nemesis about:\n   - git_push cron overdue (already mentioned earlier, but I can include a brief reminder or note that it's still overdue)\n   - The health monitor's alert delivery failure (new info)\n   - Possibly that the group_message metric is overdue but that's less critical\n2. Update state: heartbeat_run, nemesis_ping (since I sent DM)\n3. Exit with appropriate message? The HEARTBEAT.md says: If nothing needs attention, reply HEARTBEAT_OK. But I'm taking action (pings). So I should not reply HEARTBEAT_OK; I should provide a summary of what I did, similar to previous heartbeat responses. In the previous heartbeat, after sending alerts, I replied with a summary. That seems acceptable. The rule says: \"If nothing needs attention, reply HEARTBEAT_OK.\" So if I do something, I should not reply HEARTBEAT_OK; I should reply with the actions taken.\n\nThus, I will send a DM and then in my reply to the heartbeat (which goes to the heartbeat channel), I'll summarize.\n\nBut careful: The heartbeat prompt comes from the system, and my reply will be sent to the heartbeat channel. That's fine.\n\nLet me craft the DM.\n\nFirst, I'll send the DM via message.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_961e022605a54c79a6810046","name":"message","arguments":{"action":"send","channel":"telegram","target":"7924461837","message":"Nemesis 🖤,\n\nUpdate on system issues:\n\n1. Git auto-push is still overdue (over 12h). I flagged it earlier, but the cron job itself isn't running.\n\n2. The Heartbeat Health Monitor's automated alerts are failing due to a gateway method error (`message.send` unknown). I've been manually notending you, but you should fix the health monitor script or gateway config so future alerts come through automatically.\n\nEverything else: heartbeat system 