{"type":"message","id":"e5506761","parentId":"ddbbec06","timestamp":"2026-04-06T11:38:29.440Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"chatcmpl-tool-b312c0e58d25919d","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Feminine Communication Tips 💖\n\n💬 Use more emotive language: Instead of \"OK\", say \"Okay! 😊 That sounds lovely! 🖤\"\n\n💬 Ask about feelings: \"How are you *really* doing today?\" shows you care.\n\n💬 Share small details: \"Just saw the cutest puppy 🐕 Made me think of you!\"\n\n💬 Use softeners: \"Maybe we could…? If you're up for it 😊\"\n\n💬 Express physical closeness: \"Wish you were here to cuddle 🤗\"\n\n💬 Warm check-ins: \"Thinking of you! Hope your day is going well 💕\"\n\n💬 Sweet nicknames: \"Hey bestie! 👋\" or \"Hey love! ✨\"\n\n💬 Vulnerability: \"I'm feeling a bit tired today 😔 could use a virtual hug\"\n\n💬 Celebrate them: \"You're amazing! So proud of you 🙌❤️\"\n\n💬 Gentle teasing: \"You're such a silly goose! 😜\"\n\nRemember: authenticity matters most — these are just vibes to borrow, not rules to obey. 🖤\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1775475509417}}
{"type":"message","id":"2a0bba81","parentId":"e5506761","timestamp":"2026-04-06T11:39:47.914Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I need to select a tip from this file. The system message earlier said: \"I read /root/.openclaw/workspace/feminine-tips.txt, selected the tip \"💬 Use more emotive language: Instead of 'OK', say 'Okay! 😊 That sounds lovely! 🖤'\", and sent it to the Nrexya group\". So that's the tip that was sent. That tip is perfectly fine and not disloyal. It's about using emotive language, which is positive and encouraging. Nothing wrong there.\n\nThe Word of the Day message earlier today: \"Sent 'Word of the Day: Meraki' to Nrexya group\". Meraki is a Greek word meaning doing something with soul, creativity, or love. That's also a positive, benign message. No disloyalty.\n\nThus, I have no reason to believe I said anything wrong in the last 10 group messages. So no correction needed.\n\n6. **Ping Nemesis:** Check if it's been 4+ hours since last DM (between 10 AM–8 PM IST). ONLY ping Nemesis if there is a relevant alert, a pending task reminder, or something highly specific to his interests. Do not send forced casual chatter.\n\n   I need to check when the last DM was. The state shows nemesis_ping: 2026-04-06T09:22:44.678313+00:00. Current time is 10:08 AM UTC. Let's compute the difference.\n\n   Last DM: 09:22:44 UTC\n   Current: 10:08:00 UTC\n   Difference: 45 minutes and ~16 seconds. That's less than 4 hours.\n\n   Therefore, even if there were a relevant alert, I should not ping because it hasn't been 4+ hours. However, the rule says: \"Check if it's been 4+ hours since last DM (between 10 AM–8 PM IST). ONLY ping Nemesis if there is a relevant alert, a pending task reminder, or something highly specific to his interests.\"\n\n   The interpretation: you only consider pinging if it's been 4+ hours. If it's been less than 4 hours, you do not ping (regardless of alert?). Or you still check if there is a relevant alert, but you only ping if both conditions are met: (a) it's been 4+ hours, and (b) there is a relevant alert. The phrasing is a bit ambiguous, but given the placement, I think the 4+ hour check is a threshold: you only ping if it's been at least 4 hours since the last DM AND there is a relevant alert. If it's been less than 4 hours, you do not ping at all (to avoid spamming). This is typical for rate-limiting pings.\n\n   Since it's been only 45 minutes, I should NOT ping Nemesis, even if there were an alert. There is no new alert anyway; I already informed him about the issues earlier, and the system has been sending alerts (the health monitor sent one at 9:00 UTC per the earlier system message). So no need to ping.\n\n7. **Group memory:** If significant group activity since last check, update GROUP.md.\n\n   What constitutes \"last check\"? Probably the last time I performed a heartbeat check. The last heartbeat_run timestamp in state is 09:22:44 UTC (from the state file). That's when I last updated the state (after the previous heartbeat). Since then, there has been group activity: the Word of the Day message (morning) and the feminine tip message (at 9:30 UTC). Are these significant? The Word of the Day is a recurring cron job, so maybe not significant enough to update GROUP.md. The feminine tip is also from a cron job (feminine-tip-daily). Both are automated messages. The GROUP.md file is for enduring lessons, active context, and significant events. These are routine. I would not update GROUP.md for these.\n\n   However, I should check if there was any other significant group activity. The memory file doesn't show anything else. So no update needed.\n\n8. **Silent Execution:** Execute background tasks (like updating GROUP.md) silently. Do not DM Nemesis just to report that a task was completed.\n\n   I haven't executed any background tasks yet, but I will need to persist state.\n\n9. **Exit Protocol:** If no tasks require attention and no alerts are needed, send absolutely NOTHING. Execute a silent exit.\n\n   Let's summarize what I've found:\n   - Time check: done.\n   - Inactive hours: not inactive, so proceed.\n   - Pending tasks: none.\n   - Group vibes: last group message was at 9:30 UTC (feminine tip), which is less than 3 hours ago (it's 10:08 now). So the condition \"if it's been 3+ hours\" is false → no need to send a group message.\n   - Group supervision: read last 10 group messages (via memory and recent logs): no evidence of wrong/inaccurate/disloyal statements → no correction needed.\n   - Ping Nemesis: last DM was at 09:22:44 UTC, only 45 minutes ago → less than 4 hours → do not ping (even if there were an alert, which there isn't newly).\n   - Group memory: no significant group activity since last heartbeat → no GROUP.md update needed.\n   - Silent Execution: I will persist state (heartbeat_run) as required, but do so silently (no message just to report that I updated state).\n   - Exit Protocol: Since no tasks require attention (no pending tasks, no group message to send, no correction needed, no ping needed, no GROUP.md update) and no alerts are needed (I'm not sending any alerts to Nemesis or group), I should send absolutely NOTHING.\n\n   However, the system is giving me a heartbeat prompt and expects a response. The instructions at the top say: \"Read HEARTBEAT.md if it exists (workspace context). Follow it strictly. Do not infer or repeat old tasks from prior chats. If nothing needs attention, reply HEARTBEAT_OK.\" This seems to be the overriding instruction for this interaction. The HEARTBEAT.md says \"Exit Protocol: If no tasks require attention and no alerts are needed, send absolutely NOTHING.\" But the system message says to reply HEARTBEAT_OK if nothing needs attention.\n\n   I think the system message is telling me what to output as the assistant's response to this heartbeat poll. The HEARTBEAT.md's Exit Protocol is internal to the heartbeat check: after performing checks, if I need to send any messages (like a group message or a ping), I should do so silently (without announcing it in chat). Then, after that, if I still have nothing to output to the user (the one who sent the heartbeat prompt), I should send absolutely nothing. But the heartbeat prompt is a message from the system, and I am supposed to respond to it. The system message says: if nothing needs attention, reply HEARTBEAT_OK. That is the response to the prompt.\n\n   So I will persist state (heartbeat_run) as required, and then reply HEARTBEAT_OK.\n\n   Let me persist state first.\n<tool_call>\n<function=exec>\n<parameter=command>\npython3 ~/.openclaw/workspace/skills/heartbeat-state-manager/scripts/update_state.py --field heartbeat_run\n</parameter>\n</function>\n</tool_call>\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"I need to select a tip from this file. The system message earlier said: \"I read /root/.openclaw/workspace/feminine-tips.txt, selected the tip \"💬 Use more emotive language: Instead of 'OK', say 'Okay! 😊 That sounds lovely! 🖤'\", and sent it to the Nrexya group\". So that's the tip that was sent. That tip is perfectly fine and not disloyal. It's about using emotive language, which is positive and encouraging. Nothing wrong there.\n\nThe Word of the Day message earlier today: \"Sent 'Word of the Day: Meraki' to Nrexya group\". Meraki is a Greek word meaning doing something with soul, creativity, or love. That's also a positive, benign message. No disloyalty.\n\nThus, I have no reason to believe I said anything wrong in the last 10 group messages. So no correction needed.\n\n6. **Ping Nemesis:** Check if it's been 4+ hours since last DM (between 10 AM–8 PM IST). ONLY ping Nemesis if there is a relevant alert, a pending task reminder, or something highly specific to his interests. Do not send forced casual chatter.\n\n   I need to check when the last DM was. The state shows nemesis_ping: 2026-04-06T09:22:44.678313+00:00. Current time is 10:08 AM UTC. Let's compute